column5: Likely the earliest traditionally dateable sound change in Carite, and in Indo-European in general, is laryngeal colouring. As its traces can be seen even across Anatolian, it is likely that an allophonic process of vowel colouring next to the traditionally posited laryngeals *h₂ *h₃ predates the Anatolian split. This had little effect on the morphology of Indo-European early on, and only later did it influence its grammatical ablaut. A generalised overview of the process:|-|Two things are notable about this change. The first is that, as in other Indo-European languages, the effects of laryngeal colouring are recoverable only for the vowel *e, and not any other vowel; whether this is due to its effect only on this vowel, or that the effects of colouring on other vowels were lost, is indeterminable. The second is that, after this change, we cannot reliably distinguish in Carite history the laryngeals *h₁ and *h₂ later in time; one theory states that might have merged at some point immediately after colouring effects took place, phonemicising the vowel colour, and another that they remained distinguished, but that sound changes treated them the same due to their phonetic and phonological similarity.
column9:
According to some, Carite also coloured *a next to *h₃:|-|According to those in favour, the colouring of *e next to two different colouring laryngeals can be predicted if the colouring was a two-step process; first, *h₂ would colour *e to an *a, and this *a would be coloured to *o (alongside uncoloured *e) next to *h₃. However, this environment only appears to appear in a single word (pie@h₂eh₃mós, whence °OOMOS°), which makes it likely another more mainstream explanation can be found.

It is worth noting that while the Latin and Greek reflexes of *h₂o appear to be either /o/ or /a/, Carite appears to simply reflect *o for these cases.
column12: Voicing assimilation in obstruent clusters is another extremely early Indo-European phenomenon. It predates all the other recoverable processes, and its age relative to laryngeal colouring cannot be determined. The process dictates the spread of voicing from the final element in a cluster regressively.
column14: This change also operated when the cluster included aspirates: they can be assumed to also be voiced, or breathily/partially voiced, to begin with. All aspirates in such clusters presumably become voiceless aspirates, but their result cannot be shown to be different from regular voiced obstruents: presumably, this aspiration is lost early enough internally to merge their outcome with that of regular tenues, and not (the somewhat later) voiceless aspirates.
column15:
This was later generalised to all aspirates before a plosive:|-|This assimilation happened both at morpheme boundaries, and morpheme-internally (especially when triggered by ablaut):

*ni-sᵒd-ós > °NIZDOS°

The voiced consonants produced by this change were generally allophonic, only to phonemicise later when their morphophonological environment became irrecoverable.
column16: A somewhat later process, Siebs' law, changed this system after the rise and proliferation of prefixed s-mobile. Word-initial clusters with |*sB *sBʰ|, formed morphologically, would devoice, possibly giving rise to a new set of voiceless aspirates, in addition to adding to a growing number of voiceless tenues:|-|It is not clear if the voiceless aspirates remained phonemic for long - in any case, in Carite, they behave identically to the regular voiceless tenues and presumably merged shortly after if they ever were distinct in the first place. Two other large, early processes involving /*s/ took place at roughly the same time.
column17: The first was the dissolution of thorn clusters; all clusters that were underlyingly a sequence of an alveolar and velar plosive were already slightly affricated in earlier Indo-European times (reflected in xlu@īnzagan-, presumably underlyingly /-dzg-/, but not reflected, or possibly undone, in Hittite), but the development of these clusters after the split of Anatolian and Tocharian languages from the main phylum sets the late Common Indo-European group, together with Carite, apart from earlier Indo-European. In Carite, the thorn clusters underwent metathesis and deaffrication:|-|The reflex of |*T{g,ǵ}(ʷ)ʰ| as [*{g,ǵ}(ʷ)ʰz] is actually expected, since the first part of the intermediate step cluster |*dʰg(ʷ)ʰ| (after assimilation) is predictably deaspirated before a plosive, and is then affricated and metathesised.
column26: The degemination of dentals happened similarly to Greek; the first dental (i.e. alveolar plosive) was affricated, and then the resulting cluster was simplified:|-|This process probably only happened only at morpheme boundaries: the pie@átta was preserved seemingly unaltered. It is possible that the word had some other process at play, or that it was a babbled word or a loan common to Indo-European; regardless, the process continued to be a productive morphophonological alternation.
column28: Another early process in Carite history, shared with the majority of Indo-European languages, is Osthoff's law, which dictates the shortening of sequences of long vowels followed by a resonant and another, indeterminate consonant:|-|Osthoff's sequences shortened both internally and finally, and—crucial for dating the change—also happened before laryngeals that were later lost. It is especially important in Carite, being an active surface filter for a greater length of time.
column29: The first big loss of laryngeals (first laryngeal loss) happened immediately after Osthoff's law took place. It dictated the loss of some interconsonantal laryngeals, operating in two different directions:|-|The inherited Indo-European sequences of the type *ōRHC (including the diphthongs *ōy *ōw, and others) were already shortened and merged into sequences of the type *oRHC due to Osthoff's law.
column31: Centumisation in Carite took place somewhat late, and only after the coalescence of a sequence of a back velar followed by *w into a single labiovelar consonant:|-|Some fringe linguists hypothesise that this change also affected the laryngeal sequence *h₂w > *h₃, citing late-attested forms such as ?? (from *???) and ?? (hypothetically from *???, though this etymology is controversial). Others dismiss this assumption and claim that *h₂ had by then merged already with *h₁ and that it is indistinguishable from it in these contexts.
column35: Centumisation proper happened quite similarly to how it played out in Greek and Italo-Celtic: the merger of palatovelars into plain velars was straightforward and wasn't followed by any secondary, characteristically satem changes (cf. Germanic and RUKI). Centumisation is taken to have been a single, simple step:|-|Carite is peculiar in that it is possible to recover the identity of the palatovelar series before the labial *w, as they didn't coalesce into a labiovelar, and are instead preserved as *kw *kʰw *gw *gʰw. This is also present in Greek, which reflects initial *ḱw as κυ- (ku-, as in grc@κύων=kúōn 'dog', from pie@ḱwṓ; other palatovelars analogously), and (with varying peculiarities) internal *Ḱw as a geminate labiovelar instead of a short one (for example /-kk-/, as in Aeolian grc@ἴκκος=íkkos 'horse', from pie@h₁éḱwos) .
column39: Immediately following centumisation was labiovelar dissimilation, where many new Carite labiovelars, plenty of which were sourced from coalescent mergers, dissimilated at a distance. Namely, two consecutive syllables were disallowed to have labiovelars in their onsets, forcing a dissimilative loss of rounding:
column40: It was roughly at this point that everyone can agree with the first merger of laryngeals, where *h₁ merged with *h₂. It is assumed the direction of the merger was *h₁ > *h₂ due to the colouring effect the merged laryngeal had on sonorants shortly thereafter. Some linguists prefer calling the laryngeals *hₐ *hₒ from this point onwards, referring to their colouring effects, but this usage is not adopted here.
column41: At roughly the same time, the first loss of laryngeals occurred:
column42: One of the changes that lead to the distinguishing of Carite from its now diverging cousins is the vocalisation of sonorants that worked in several stages. The first to be vocalised were sonorants next to a laryngeal:
column48: Next, an epenthetic vowel was inserted to take up the syllabicity of any remaining sonorant. Where exactly this sound was inserted, if the sonorant was remained and if the vowel was a schwa Indogermanicum depended on the environment:
column51: The same schwa was inserted after an interconsonantal laryngeal surrounded by true consonants:
column52: Due to the later diphthong reflexes of certain sequences of syllabic laryngeal and semivowel, and their lack of interaction with the preceding consonants, most caritologists also postulate a third schwa-insertion rule:|-|The length of diphthong in question (and, as a result, the position of the schwa relative to the laryngeal) are ultimately irretrievable due to Osthoff's law. The quality of the vowel in early Carite °PAWYOS° < pie@ph₂wyós shows the lack of interaction between the schwa and the first consonant (otherwise, **pūjos would have been expected).
column53: This schwa took up rounding from any previous consonant, though *w curiously enough did not appear to take part in this process, possibly due to its semivocalic nature:
column55: Due to the regressive action of the boukolos rule (Carite does not seem to reflect the progressive version of this law that well, or—according to some—at all), this delabialised any labiovelar after which it occured:
column56: The schwa took colour from the previous laryngeal much like older *e:
column58: The schwa also picked up rounding from a following *m, but not any other labial:|-|Notably, this rule postdates the colouring of post-laryngeal schwas as the coloured schwas did not become a high vowel, and instead merged with the older mid vowels.
column59: Finally, it lost its distinctiveness by becoming a generic unrounded high vowel:
column60: It is likely that at this point the laryngeals lost differentiation and merged into one general laryngeal continuant, completing the second merger of laryngeals:
column61: The next loss of laryngeals (second laryngeal loss) happened to sequences of vowels with a laryngeal:|-|The lengthening of contracted laryngeal sequences still obeyed Osthoff's law, shortening the new vowels when followed by a resonant and then an obstruent. Examples of this process are scant, but evident in the so-called conjunctive nominals, which, in early Carite, take special forms in subordinated clauses and in coordinated clauses; a typical example of this is the masculine noun °EKWOS°, its genitive plural attested both as the regular ekwōm and in the conjunctive form ekwomfe; the length of the vowel in the suffix is indicative of Osthoff's law.
column63: An unusual, but well-documented Carite change is the effect of laryngeals on consonants in word-initial position. They voiced obstruents and fortified semivowels, probably through a process of glottalisation:|-|A longstanding hypothesis is that the fortition of *Hy resulted in *ḱ, which was still unmerged, but otherwise invisible to historical linguistics. This opinion is somewhat controversial, but unfalsifiable due to our inability to elucidate which exact allophone *y fortited to. This change is occasionally termed Engels' law, and it was first posited by the Limburgish philologist Klaus Engels.
column70: After this, the laryngeals fail to effect any further changes, and are likely lost shortly thereafter, completing the third laryngeal loss:
column71: Word-initial laryngeal voicing of *s enables the dating of another change, its word-initial debuccalisation:
column72: This change was probably concurrent with the deaspiration of obstruents after nasals:
column73: Another concurrent change was the debuccalisation of word-initial prevocalic *gʰ:|-|It is probable that this change would also have affected word-initial *gʷʰ → *ɦʷ, but the labiovelarisation of its rounding probably reverted the change shortly thereafter, putting it at → *gʷʰ again.
column74: The collapse of the four-way contrast system followed shortly thereafter. The aspiration feature of voiced aspirates would combine with their voicing to produce a breathy phonation, which merged with voiceless tenues. A possible glottalic interpretation is that in these early Carite stages voicing was a creaky or glottalised feature (explaining laryngeal voicing of word-initial obstruents), and that breathy segments had more in common acoustically with voiceless tenues. Regardless, the internal history of this change is opaque, and we only posit:|-|Notably, this change did not affect word-initial *h derived from older *gʰ, as it had already merged with the reflex of initial *s, but did affect all internal instances of *gʰ—even those that were preserved as a result of prefixation.
column78: Long-distance assimilation of labial *p into a following *kʷ likely happened around this time:
column79: It was roughly at this time that the more lenis labiovelar plosives *kʷ *gʷ lost their velar plosion, but retained the lower frequency timbre of velarisation by labiodentalising instead of merely shifting to labials:
column81: When any vowel was followed by *i *u, the sequence collapsed into a diphthong with *i *u surfacing as the semivowels *y *w. If they were formerly stressed, the stress shifted to the preceding vowel.
column83: Certain homorganic vowel-sonorant sequences coalesced into trimoraic vowels:
column85: The coalescence was the first part of a more prevalent collapse of certain homosyllabic diphthongs:|-|Notably, the collapse didn't affect sequences like *yV, nor the high vowels resulting from a laryngeal schwa. Osthoff's Law was clearly still productive at this stage, with e.g. pie@swéydoh₂ first becoming *séydō as the resulting *ē was shortened before predictably becoming °SWEYDOO°.
column98: A few other consonant changes date to roughly this period, without an easy way to date them with precision relative to the rest of Carite developments of this time:
column108: Somewhere around this time, the short high vowels *i *u underwent heavier modification:
column112: This was likely concurrent with this change pertaining to vowel length:
column113: Stressed *ē *ō were raised in stressed syllables:
column115: Unstressed trimoraic vowels were reduced to their long counterparts:
column118: A surface filter of nasal assimilation that applied across Carite history is also dated to have started up to this point in time:|-|It is worth noting that *m did not appear to assimilate into *n before *n, which was retained as the sequence *mn instead.
column120: The change that is taken to define Carite as a fully independent language in its own ecosystem is Verner's Carite law, a structural parallel of Verner's law in Germanic. Onsets of stressed, internal Carite syllables were voiced, and when the distinctive position of accent was lost to a word-initial accent relocation, the voicing phonemicised completely:|-|The voicing is likely to initially have affected only the onset of the stressed syllable that caused it, but voicing assimilation rules for clusters spread the voicing to the whole cluster.
column125: Word-initial /w/, which only appeared before liquids or vowels, either fortited into /b/ or lenited into /h/, respectively:
column127: It is assumed that /s/ debuccalised word-finally when following a vowel at roughly the same time:
column128: A short, unstressed vowel is deleted when directly preceding a long vowel.
column129: Intervocalic semivowels appeared to geminate in specific environments, triggering Osthoff's law when relevant:|-|It is likely this change originally caused alterations due to vowels differing between suffixes. However, analogy must have occurred at some point after this. (to do)
column131: Following the change above, it is likely that sequences of a vowel and a semivowel, at least preconsonantally or word-finally, started being considered a single diphthong. This notably did not affect overlong vowels, which remained a sequence as cna be seen later. Some reconstruct an actual change, others find this distinction rather meaningless. Nonetheless, it is presented here:
column133: Dissimilation of the previously geminated semivowels must have taken place at some point after, causing a shift in the distribution of diphthongs:
column135: Around the same time, it is likely hiatuses were resolved using a prop semivowel. This appears to have been /w/ before back vowels and /j/ everywhere else:
column137: Some posit a metathesis of an intervocalic NL sequence - however, due to the extreme limited distribution, it is possible this change was not systematic but just happened to affect both retrievable examples:
column139: The few remaining overlong vowels appear to have broken into a longer sequence:|-|While some claim this change can be posited with absolutely certainty to have taken place after the intervocalic semivowel gemination, this is not entirely sure: after all, the semivowels included in these sequences would be the results of the hiatus resolutions.
column141: The sequence /jo/ appears to have metathesised into /oi̯/ when word-initial or postconsonantally:|-|This mostly affected the genitive singular form of the o-stems, but has at least one lexeme on its name.
column142: Short mid vowels are raised in stressed syllables:
column144: /h/ presumably gained [x] as an allophone next to non-front vowels:|-|Considering the inclusion of /a(ː)/ as a trigger, some prefer to reconstruct this change to involve back vowels instead and use it as an argument in favour of a possible realisation of /a(ː)/ as [ɑ(ː)] - however, not everyone adheres to this notion.
column147: This change also affected the same sequence when followed by another nasal:

column362: §ed_greek reconstructs the Proto-Germanic etymon with *-ī- although §ed_germanic disagrees. While the *l~n alteration may date back to Proto-Indo-European times, it is more likely we are dealing with two separate derivations, a view which is supported by the difference in length. While the Germanic form may be traced back to the diminutive suffix *-ilaz, either Hoffmann's suffix *-hₓn- or the derivational *-ihₓnos may be identified in the Graeco-Armeno-Carite derivation. The presence of an o-grade in Armenian as well as its classification as an ea-stem points towards an independent Armenian derivation, while it is impossible to point out if the Graeco-Carite derivations, which are formally identical, are independent or areal innovations. While the association between hedgehogs and snakes appears to be common and a linguistic analysis of hedgehog as "snake-eater" checks out zoologically, an actual derivation only makes sense phonologically in Greek as its word for snake, grc@ἔχις=ékhis, would be the only pure reflex of a hypothetical pie@h₁éǵʰis, being displaced by pie@h₃égʷʰis in other branches. Any corruption of reflexes of the latter or of the lexeme for hedgehog in descendants must thus be secondary.

column362: Once explained as an n-infix of pie@sep- with a *-yós suffix. However, this preform **sn̥pyós would yield *himbjos and, as such, the first vowel is unexpected. An alternative reconstruction of the root, which §ed_latin prefers, is pie@seh₁p-, leading to **sn̥h₁pyós > *snābjos. If we assume a vrddhi-derivative *sh₁ep- (which would also explain the short vowels in pgmc@safjaną and grc@ἕπω=hépō), we may start from a zero-grade **sh₁n̥pyós > *hambjos, which would also result into an unexpected first vowel. This discrepancy, combined with the uncertainty of the root as pointed out by §ed_germanic and §ed_latin, may point towards a (possibly common) substrate origin instead.

column362: The actual pronunciation of this Gaulish month is up for debate as the expected outcome of Proto-Celtic *kʷ would be Gaulish p. It is possible the spelling in the attestation was archaic and the actual pronunciation included /p/ or that it was restored to /kʷ/ through Latin influence. The Carite reflex, which goes back to the generalisation of the *-ios suffix found in other months, not only shows a velar, but also the vocalisation of the labial element. However, this is inconclusive for the Gaulish pronunciation as it may be an early borrowing before the shift of labiovelars or borrowed from a dialect which retained this pronunciation for longer.

column362: The word for "cat" is generally said to come from a non-Indo-European language, quite possibly a North-African one, which then spread across Europe, possibly through Latin. This view is adopted in this dictionary for the sake of convenience; however, it is far from certain. Reconstructions lead back to a root *katt- which, besides in Latin, is present identically in Proto-Celtic and Gaulish and, slightly further away, in Germanic. As such, it is possible the Carite root did not have lat@cattus as intermediate step or that it borrowed it from a Celtic language.

column362: The Latin outcome is irregular and may be through folk etymology, possibly through analogy with lat@vīvus? Balto-Slavic cognates are mentioned in multiple sources but seemingly missing from §ed_slavic. §ed_germanic attempts to connect the seemingly unrelated Germanic reflex by including a laryngeal, yielding the root *h₂wer-. However, this would also surface in the reduplications as *h₂ey-, *h₂wi-, *h₂i- and even *h₂oy-, making this a very ad hoc solution. His explanation, being that the daughters independently restored the reduplication after the loss of laryngeals, is unconvincing. As suggested by §oxf_intro among others, by analysing the Germanic formation as a compound of the word of oak, pgmc@aiks, and the Proto-Indo-European root *wer- reconstructed by the other scholars, we may solve the puzzle without any new issues emerging.

column362: The actual reconstruction of the root differs between authors, with the middle laryngeal being reconstructed both as *h₁ and *h₂. While this is irrelevant to the outcome in Carite, *h₂ seems more likely due to the Doric variant λᾶνος (lânos), if not a hyperdorism. More prevalent is the reconstruction with with an initial *h₂-. This laryngeal is reconstructed on the basis of the initial ḫ- in Hittite. §ed_celtic ascribes this to metathesis however, as neither Greek form shows any trace of the expected word-initial α-. While §ed_greek says the laryngeal might have been there originally, it must have vanished disappeared early in Greek history, possibly through dissimilation. The presence of the laryngeal would not affect the Carite outcome as Engels' law would require *h₂w- to be followed by a vowel. As pointed out by §ed_germanic, the Germanic reflex requires a suffix-stressed form which slightly deviates from the others; however, §pie_to_pgmc departs from a radically stressed form instead.

column362: A word with a complicated etymology. The similarity of the first syllable to the Greek and Sanskrit forms is striking. However, the suffix of the Sanskrit form as well as the existence of san@वर्तक=vartaka points towards a later application of a productive Sanskrit suffix. The Greek suffixes tend to vascillate between γ/κ (g/k) which may point towards a Pre-Greek origin; however, this may just be a later analogical procedure. If a native word, grc@ὄρτυξ=órtux would be the expected result of *wórtogʷs where the voiced labiovelar would explain the voiced velar reflex (regularly delabialised through the boukólos rule after the application of Cowgill's law). However, if this were the case, we would expect *v in Carite. As such, the exact origin remains uncertain.

column362: The original root noun was clearly archaic and is only preserved in a handful of branches such as Greek. It was later reformed, occasionally as an u-stem but mostly as an o-stem with the later transfer to the fourth declension is because of the feminine gender. The generalisation of ն (n) in Armenian, which is the word-final reflex of *m, shows that the thematicisation took place after this generalisation had already spread throughout the paradigm. While at a first glance, Carite is isolated in reforming the word as an i-stem, the global remodelling of root nouns as i-stem explains this phenomenon. While u-stems also underwent this transfer, the expected result would have been *domwī. As such, we may convincingly state that Carite, like Armenian, preserved the root noun until the remodelling took place.
column364: Sun Jul 12 2020 01:01:15 GMT+0200 (Central European Summer Time)

column359: lat bōs,san गौः=gáuḥ,grc βοῦς=boûs,tchA ko,tchB keu,hye կով=kov,pclt bāws,pgmc kōz,pslv govę̀do,eng cow
column362: While §ed_germanic reconstructs the alteration *kō- ~ *kū-, §pie_to_pgmc retains the labiovelar in *kʷō-. The unexpected anlaut in the Latin reflex is explainable a an Osco-Umbrian loan. sqi@ka may also be related. The original Proto-Indo-European form is slightly troublesome, as we can clearly reconstruct pie@gʷeh₃- from derivatives, and the most logical approximation would be the u-stem *gʷeh₃us. However, we would expect *gʷeh₃wih₂ as regular Pre-Carite outcome, which would result into a long vowel. One could theoretically posit the generalisation of the oblique stem *gʷh₃ew-, which would be an isolated occurrence in Carite. Perhaps it is the result of a hypercorrection of the undoing of Szemerényi's law?

column362: A word with a problematic etymology. The first element is often compared to pie@séh₂l̥ ("salt"), whence °SALT° - however, this leaves the the *p unexplained. Given the presence of a *-d- extension in Armenian and Germano-Balto-Slavic, often as a u-stem, one may posit a pre-form **séh₂l̥dwih₂ with regular remodeling as i-stem. Unfortunately, this would result in Late Proto-Carite *halbi and the devoicing of the labial would be irregular. However, given the fact that the early Carite speakers presumably did not have access to the sea until not long before the Narbonne attestations and they only were familiar with sweetwater fishes, this word may be of substrate origin instead. Alternatively, this word may be a derivative of pie@selp- (whence °SELPOS), with "(fish) oil" being generalised to "fish". However, the vocalism would be unexpected.

column359: tchA ñom,tchB ñem,grc ὄνομα=ónoma,pclt anman,sqi emër,pslv jьmę,pgmc namōn,eng name,hye անուն=anun,lat nōmen,san नामन्=nā́man,hit 𒆷𒀀𒈠𒀭=lāman
column362: A word with multiple suggested protoforms. While the first laryngeal is sometimes reconstructed as *h₁ or even *h₂, the consensus appears to be that the word-initial ο- (o-) of Greek appears to confirm the identity of *h₃. The majority seems to agree on *Hnéh₃- as a reconstruction - however, §oxf_intro, §sketch_albanian, §ed_celtic and §sketch_armenian reconstruct the root without a laryngeal and posit a single *o while §dic_gaulish simply reconstructs *nom-. The function of the second laryngeal appears to be to account for the discrepancy in terms of vowel length, as one may posit full grades and zero grades. One of the main arguments against the reconstruction of the second laryngeal appears to be the fact Tocharian retains a clear reflex of *ē. In order to account for this, §pie_to_pgmc reconstructs a third ablaut grade, being a lengthened e-grade, as this would prevent the laryngeal from colouring. §ed_greek suggests dissimilation of the second laryngeal to *h₁ instead. Either way, the lack of vowel length in Carite is clear. As **n̥h₃m- would likely have resulted in **nōm-, one could ask if the version with laryngeal is problematic for Carite. However, it is possible the preceding laryngeal prevented the lengthening - after all, there are no other comparable cases with word-initial *Hn̥HC.

column362: A word with a slightly problematic etymology. While the appurtenance of Greek and Sanskrit is very attractive, the Sanskrit form poses formal problems. For this reason, alternative etymologies are often posited, such as *wor(hₓ)dʰwo- for the Graeco-Aryan reflexes. However, there are no traces of a possible digamma in Mycenaean. If one would adhere to this theory, the only proof of *h₃ would expire, leading to many to reconstruct *h₂ instead, even though this is incompatible with the Carite reflex. *h₁, which is also sometimes reconstructed, is incompatible with the Germanic full grade. §ed_germanic posits an old compound of pie@h₃er- and pie@dʰeh₁-, although the loss of the second laryngeal would be puzzling. If the alternate etymology of Graeco-Aryan is applied to Carite, we would end up with an old **urdwos rather than *ordwos. However, considering the earliest attestation of this lexeme is a hapax legomenon, we may be dealing with a deviating form, and the merger of both options into *urdwos that followed makes it only more uncertain. No matter what the original etymology is, the Carite form seems to be closely linked to the Greek reflex.

The Carite etymology is often reconstructed with an e-grade as an example of how an *e adjacent to both *h₂ and *h₃ would result into *o - however, this claim is made worthless by positing an o-grade instead.
